<|startoftext|>If it wasn't for the awesome customer service from Abigail I was going to give this place another shot, but I got carried away.\n\nWe went for a late night late night dinner on our way to Vegas.  The place was packed for dinner on a Sunday night.  It took us about 15 minutes to clear our plates.\n\nThe food was delicious. We got the chorizo, buffalo cauliflower, and beef fritters.  The chicken fritter was made with beef curry and it was wonderful.  We also got the grilled salmon, pago, and cheese sticks.  There were also a few other items on the menu (like the grilled corn and garlic mashed potatoes) that were good. \n\nFor $14 we got a nice selection of food and the food was pretty good.  I think the price is on the high end for Vegas dining, but I wouldn't spend a lot of my money here.  But it was good food.<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>The food was excellent! I think I loved all of the food except the crab and the shrimp. The service was outstanding as well. The ambience was great; the bar is the highlight of the establishment. The restaurant is a great spot to hang out with your friends. I love that they are open all the time, even in the summer. My only complaint is that I think I can get food poisoning at this establishment every year if I eat the fish\/snakes\/bread and never get any of the over-acidified stomaches.\n\nI highly recommend this restaurant!!<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Food for a group on a Sunday evening around 10.  The menu is minimal and simple. We ordered the lobster spaghetti, crab legs, and sushi burrito.  The menu says it is a 4 to 0 rice which I would have thought was fine since I can always get it in my preferred jap.  We settled on 4.00 and the man was happy to oblige.\n\nThe lobster spaghetti was quite good.  I wouldn't say that it was the best I've ever had.  The lobster was quite tough.  In fact, I think if I'd stuck to their other dishes, the dish that came out would have been a little softer than lobster.  The crab legs were also good but not great.  I'll stick to the seafood.  The burrito was decent.  They had a variety of seafood options and the sauce was strong.\n\nOther side dishes we've had here include a pork chop, and two entree salads.   The pork chop was good, but not fantastic.  I don't think you can get a better pork chop in Las Vegas.\n\nThe sushi burrito was excellent from the fish to the rice and sauce.  \n\nIt's one of the few restaurants that I have eaten in Las Vegas at that price point.  The sushi here is good, especially the crab legs.  They do a good job of creating a meal and I can't complain about that.<|endoftext|>
